passages.text: Mixed results and we cut numbers reflecting the lowered guidance. But fundamentals not key driver of share price into YE; stock is a special sit with many scenarios around Prosus, an activist investor, and potential to highlight value. We like the trade into YE.

All in a mixed set of numbers with trimmed guidance on a clean basis on GMV (slightly), EBITDA and FCF (albeit the company argues largely down to FX, where the message is a bit confusing), some more investment in Korea EBITDA ex FX (albeit with improving recent share trends and good progress on value proposition) and more cash out than expected in 2H at €450m related to Spain legal dispute (albeit some was likely, it could return if DH is successful in its legal and political cases and it was already in our EV/Equity bridge). But fundamentals don't really matter to calling the share price into the end of the year, in our view. There are many, many scenarios ahead. But we see a clear incentive for the Management and Supervisory Boards to look at options to crystallise value in the SOTP and raise funds in the context of an activist investor on the board, who could have more influence if Prosus steps away at some point (see our take on the recent EC Prosus/JET/DH situation (here)); the potential for suitors to still look at the company given the depressed valuation and the wave of consolidation the industry is in; and a scenario where Prosus needs to sell \(>20\%\) of the shares. We understand concerns that Prosus selling \(>20\%\) of the DH share capital into the market could be bad for the share price if not handled in a smart way. But, given the EC has given Prosus nearly 12 months to exit and Prosus is presumably incentivised to exit at as high of a price as possible, we see little logic in Prosus starting to place the DH shares into the market in the short term and see it as more likely that Prosus waits to find a better moment over time. We also still think there is a scenario where Prosus could come back to look at DH again, as it reportedly did last summer (e.g., FT, 28 Oct 2024, here) - to do so would require closing on JET (likely in October), quickly finding a solution for the 5 markets of overlap, and then re- engaging with the EC around concerns on disincentives to open new markets were both companies owned by Prosus. This may not be possible - we don't have perfect visibility into the legal nuance - and is just one scenario. Ultimately, we don't have a clear opinion on exactly what happens next. But we do have a view that the DH stock does not reflect its SOTP value and the key stakeholders in the company have an interest in changing that. We like the risk / reward into YE. Maintains OW, PT to €43.50.

**Changes to forecasts.** We trim GMV estimates both for FX and on an u/l basis. We have 8% GMV growth, incl discontinued items (i.e., 10% on a company adj. lfl basis). We lower EBITDA in '25E to €918m, the mid point of the new guidance range. These downgrades follow into '26E and beyond. We also factor in the cash payments in 2H around the EC/Glovo settlement (€329m) and the Spain escrow (€450m), but remove the offsetting liabilities in provisions and contingent liabilities in our valuation methodology, which is based off of '25E net debt. Our PT comes down to €43.50 from €45.70 as a result of these changes.

Delivery Hero has the most forward-thinking vision of the EU delivery aggregators, in our view. It is a space on which we are positive, and that flows into our assessment of the investment case. We view the stock as cheap on a GMV multiple at these levels.
**Upside case** **EUR 89.30**
Delivery Hero delivers on growth and profitability forecasts and there is a sharp re-rating.
**Downside case** **EUR 11.50**
Our downside case is a stress case where industry goes ex growth and DH retrenches sharply to profit pools.
**Upside/Downside scenarios**

FY25 guidance revised lower on clean basis. The company is now expected to grow at the upper end of the previously- guided range of \(8 - 10\%\) yoy like- for- like basis at constant FX and exhyperinflationary accounting. The only nuance is that guidance is now excluding discontinued operations - these adjustments contributed \(\sim 2\) pts to growth in H1, and are expected to have a similar impact in H2. So, at the mid point, the Ifl GMV guide is 1pt lower than prior. 2) Group revenue is forecast to grow \(22 - 24\%\) yoy (vs. \(17 - 19\%\) prior). Again, the basis has changed a bit to now adjust for discontinued ops. We assume the main reason is the accelerated 1P roll out in Korea. 3) Adj. EBITDA has been revised down to €900- 940m (vs. €975- 1,025m prior). 4) FCF revised down to over €120m (vs. over €200m). The company attributes the EBITDA and FCF downgrade mainly to FX with the strengthening of the EUR vs. USD- pegged currencies and KWR, negatively impacting EBITDA by \(\sim \in 110m\) and FCF by \(\sim \in 80m\) . The company mentioned that excluding FX headwinds, it would have been on track to meet its prior FY25 guidance (in fact maths suggests slightly ahead). On the call management explained that visibility on FX was limited at the Q1 results, and while FX movements had already occurred, they weren't budgeting on spot at the time. With more stable trends emerging further into Q2, the company now has greater confidence in the FX impact, has re- adjusted FX forecasts, and has adjusted guidance accordingly.

South Korea update. Management reiterated expectations for a return to GMV growth in Q4 in local FX. Q2 GMV declined somewhat narrowed vs. Q1 as operational trends improved. We expect Q3 comps to remain tough due to elevated subsidies last year, but Q4 should benefit from easier base effects (paid subscription kicked in from October). Own delivery share rose to \(70\%\) in Q2 vs. \(35\%\) a year ago; ahead of management expectations. Management says that unit economics on OD are better than expected but the net is still negative to EBITDA given that OD has a lower contribution margin than marketplace. The company is now indicating that EBITDA will be down yoy in local FX (prior broadly stable / slightly up). The company believes the value proposition is improving (e.g., subscription, Meal for One etc.) and has plenty of further product development to come.

Glovo tech stack integration completed. DH completed the full integration of Glovo into its unified global tech platform in Q2. As of now, all brands except Woowa (South Korea) are operating off of the central platform. Korea continues to run on a separate tech stack, with integration expected to be completed by end- Q1 2026. Operational KPI improvements post Glovo integration: c. \(+7\%\) uplift in conversion, c. \(- 10\%\) fewer late orders, c. \(- 10\%\) reduction in cost per order, and a \(+29\%\) increase in ad revenue.

Talabat stake update - no plans sell. Management confirmed there is no intention to sell any of the Talabat stake at current valuations. This is helpful, in our view, to the degree that this has been an overhang on the Talabat stock.

Provisions & contingent liabilities H2/FY25. Continent liabilities are up to €520- 860m (still moving to employment model in Spain during 1H; now done) vs. the €440- 770m at FY. Provisions down to €618m vs. €900m due to the release of the provision related to the Glovo EC dispute (still on balance sheet in other financial liabilities). Delivery Hero confirmed it received new reclassification decisions from Spanish authorities in July, triggering payment demands totalling \(\sim \in 450m\) . This will be held in escrow whilst the cases are debated but is cash out to the business in 2H'25. Separately, the €329m EU antitrust settlement is also due this quarter. We have reflected this in our estimates for 2H, resulting in a notably cash outflow in 2H (we finish end of year with €2.0bn cash).

MENA update. Estimating EBITDA ex Talabat is not totally straight forward given it isn't a perfect translation (accounting of IV vs. Platform). But there does appear to have been some investment in Other MENA in 1H. The tone on Saudi is still reasonable, with \(>20\%\) yoy order growth in Q2, slightly higher than Q1. Management commented there is some incremental investment but in the low double- digit €m amount. There is incremental investment in Turkey, where DH continues to roll out 1P. Management expects Turkey to return to positive adj. EBITDA in H2, supported by better operational efficiency. Our estimate is that Turkish growth slowed somewhat in Q2 vs. Q1 on an u/l basis (adjusting for hyperinflationary accounting).

Asia (ex- SK) update. In APAC, the business has re- entered a growth trajectory, with broad- based volume recovery following leadership changes. We assume DH is still losing share in some of these markets to Grab.

Valuation Methodology: We value Delivery Hero on a SOTP given the regions have different market positions and growth rates. We use a DCF for each region (2- 4% terminal growth and varying WACCs, factoring in higher discount rates for emerging markets). We use a 0.2x multiple for the Integrated Verticals segment (Dark Stores) We then add in a value for tax losses and the minority stakes.

Risks which May Impede the Achievement of the Barclays Research Valuation and Price Target: To the downside, the main risks are that (1) competition increases across the various markets (both in food delivery and grocery) and (2) capital allocation gets more complicated.
